You use extractors like `Json<T>`. Here’s an example: 

```rust
use axum::{extract::Json, routing::post, Router};
use serde::Deserialize;

#[derive(Deserialize)]
struct NewUser {
    name: String,
}

async fn create_user(Json(payload): Json<NewUser>) -> String {
    format!("Created user: {}
", payload.name)
}

fn main() {
    let app = Router::new()
        .route("/users", post(create_user));
    // Run it as above
}
```
This lets you define a request body that matches the NewUser struct, then extract and validate data before processing.

You wrap your router with layers that apply to all routes inside them. For example: 

```rust
use axum::{middleware::{from_request}, routing::get, Router};

async fn log_middleware<B>(req: Request<Body>, next: Next<B>) -> Result<Response, Infallible> {
    println!("Handling {}
", req.uri());
    next.run(req).await
}

fn main() {
    let app = Router::new()
        .route("/users", get(handler_users))
        .layer(from_request(log_middleware));
}
```
You can wrap the whole router or nest layers.

Use `Arc` to share state safely between threads. Here’s an example: 

```rust
use axum::{routing::get, Router};
use std::sync::Arc;

struct AppState {
    db_pool: sqlx::PgPool,
}

async fn handler_users(state: axum::extract::State<AppState>) -> String {
    let pool = &state.db_pool;
    format!("Database connected!
")
}

fn main() {
    let state = Arc::new(AppState { db_pool: /* initialize your database */ });

    let app = Router::new()
        .route("/users", get(handler_users))
        .with_state(state);
}
```
Wrapping the data in an `Arc` lets you share it across handlers.

Yes. You can define your own error types and use `Result` with proper error codes. For example: 

```rust
use axum::{response::IntoResponse, Json};
use serde_json::json;

#[derive(thiserror::Error, Debug)]
pub enum AppError {
    #[error("Not Found")]
    NotFound,
}

impl IntoResponse for AppError {
    fn into_response(self) -> axum::response::Response {
        Json(json!({"error": self.to_string()})).into_response()
    }
}

async fn handler_users() -> Result<String, AppError> {
    Err(AppError::NotFound)?;
    Ok("List all users"
)}
```
This lets you define custom errors and return JSON responses with HTTP codes.

